  review        = {In this paper the authors propose a neural network based mechanism to classify post-disaster images and aid in rescuing decisions. Their approach is two use machine learning (ML) and deep learning (DL) algorithms to inspect photographies of a post-disaster environment taken from disaster relief organizations and detect if there are humans needing rescuing. The architecture is divided in three layers: data collection, pre-processing and image classification. First, images are retrieved from specific datasets and social media from disaster relief organizations in the data collection phase. Then, manual filtering, labeling, normalization and transformation of images are performed in the pre-processing phase, to ensure relevance of selected images. Finally, in the image classification phase, ML and DL algorithms are used to classify images, searching for humans or humans body parts. This final classification is then used to aid first responders and decision makers in the rescuing process, prioritizing sites with higher probability of victims, thus, saving as many lives as possible. To evaluate their proposal, the authors tested two ML techniques: Support Vector Machines (SVM) and Artificial Neural Networks (ANN); and three DL techniques: ResNet-50, Inception V3 and AlexNet. These techniques were tested aganst a dataset of images from the earthquake-hit regions of Tohoku, Japan. They found that ResNet-50 and Intercepvion V3 overperformed all the other techniques. For future work, the authors aim to integrate information from other sources as text from social media.

