  review        = {In this paper the authors developed a mobile application for Emergency Notifications (EN). The work emphasizes the importance of human notifications of emergencies. Although there are sensing technology to detect some emergency situations, human interaction is of high accuracy as people surrouding the affected area can quickly describe what is happening to authorities. For large-scale situations as flooding, earthquakes, etc., social media is already being used for detection, as people usually post messages and multimedia data of such events, while automated tools can mine social media data to detect such emergencies. When facing small-scale events, as a car accident, social media is not very useful because the amount of messages posted by surrouding people have a small significance compared to the total number of messages in a social network, thus, making it difficult for detection. Instead of relying in social media for small-scale emergencies, the authors state that specific EN applications are more accurate and useful. In this context, they developed an application taking into consideration its ease of use and effectiveness. To evaluate their mobile application, they performed two tests: an usability test and a simulated test. In the usability test, they asked some participants to try and use the application as if there was an emergency, to test the usability of the interface. The results of this first test were satisfactory: 60% of the users stated that they would use the application as a witness and 30% would use both as a witness and as a victim. In the simulated test, they asked some participants to install and try the application in their smartphones. After a while, a simulated car accident suddenly started in the surrouding, so the paticipants could use the application to report the emergency. After the test, authorities were asked to evaluate the results and they were satisfactory: photos and videos of the accident were of great importance, because it would made possible for the emergency operator to quickly know what kind of situation has occured and how to proceed. Also, the GPS information could provide the operators an accurate localization of the emergency, instead of relying of people's description. The authors concluded that this approach for emergency reporting does not substitude an ordinary emergency call, but can improve the accuracy of emergency reports.

